Review: “Talk to me” at its core is about vulnerability. The demon world is at its strongest when it attaches to a vulnerable host, and when it can use those vulnerabilities to wreak havoc. Though it presents a demonic, fantasy realm, this movie feels real and more relatable than some other horror movies. This movie presents the allure of seeing reality differently than you normally do. I feel like this movie has a proportionately high amount of heart-thumping scenes. Rarely does it keep its foot off of the gas, and it does not take very long at all to feel possessed by its world.

Its plot is nothing new—at times it is reminiscent of “Truman Show”, “Elf” (with, fittingly, Will Ferrel), and “Don’t Worry Darling” (unfortunately) to name a few—but it is unique in its style that is Greta’s own. My favorite moments of Barbie came from the jabby conversations between characters. Review: It seemed to me that Joker set out to be a more realistic superhero movie; for example, it wanted the world of Gotham city to be more realistic. Realistic like NYC. Very much like NYC. Joker isn’t a born villain...he’s a victim of psychological issues, a mentally ill mother, and a cold society. Review: One of my favorite Netflix horror movies (not saying a lot)

Claudia and Sandro stand together on top of a cathedral. There feels like there could be love between them. They both feel free, unbridled, relieved after so much tension. They stand admiring the architecture of the nearby buildings; the buildings are classical, monumental, beautiful. Sandro reflects on his own previous experience as an architect; he believed that it was worthwhile once, a passion once, until he became a sell-out. Claudia assures him that he can still make beautiful things. To…
